        <name>16.1.5.2 Summation forms</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Write the following finite series in summation form:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;\(\displaystyle {@SA4@} =\)&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;table style="margin-left: 2.5em;margin-top: 1em;"&gt;
            &lt;tbody&gt;
                &lt;tr&gt;
                    &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans1_upp]]&lt;/td&gt;
                    &lt;td&gt;[[validation:ans1_upp]]&lt;/td&gt;
                &lt;/tr&gt;
                &lt;tr&gt;
                    &lt;td style="text-align:center"&gt;\(\displaystyle \sum_{p ~=~ 1}\)&lt;/td&gt;
                    &lt;td style="vertical-align:top"&gt;[[input:ans1_sum]] [[validation:ans1_sum]]&lt;/td&gt;
                &lt;/tr&gt;
            &lt;/tbody&gt;
        &lt;/table&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;\(\displaystyle - \frac{1}{{@simplify(1+const2)@} \times (1 + (100)^2)} +\frac{1}{{@simplify(2+const2)@} \times (1 - (200)^2)} -\frac{1}{{@simplify(3+const2)@} \times (1 + (300)^2)} + \ldots +\frac{1}{{@simplify(8+const2)@} \times (1 - (800)^2)}=\)&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;table style="margin-left: 2.5em;margin-top: 1em;"&gt;
            &lt;tbody&gt;
                &lt;tr&gt;
                    &lt;td&gt;[[input:ans2_upp]] [[validation:ans2_upp]]&lt;/td&gt;
                    &lt;td&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
                &lt;/tr&gt;
                &lt;tr&gt;
                    &lt;td style="text-align:center"&gt;\(\displaystyle \sum_{p ~=~ 1}\)&lt;/td&gt;
                    &lt;td style="vertical-align:top"&gt;[[input:ans2_sum]] [[validation:ans2_sum]]&lt;/td&gt;
                &lt;/tr&gt;
            &lt;/tbody&gt;
        &lt;/table&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;To find the summation forms of each series, we need to obtain suitable expressions for the 'typical term'. For us this is the \(p^{th}\)-term, since both series are indexed by \(p\). And \(p\) will take values \(1,\, 2,\, 3,\, \ldots,\, n\), for some
    integer \(n\) that we must also find.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;To find an expression for the typical term, we can look at the first three terms of the series, where \(p=1,\,2\) and \(3\), respectively. Let's start with the numerator. For \(p=1\) we have \({@num(ser1(1))@}\), for \(p=2\) we have \({@num(ser1(2))@}\),
            and for \(p=3\) we have \({@num(ser1(3))@}\). The expression \({@num(ta1)@}\) is then appropriate for the numerator of the typical term. &lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Now, for the denominator we have \({@denom(ser1(1))@}\) for \(p=1\), \({@denom(ser1(2))@}\) for \(p=2\) and \({@denom(ser1(3))@}\) for \(p=3\). Then \({@denom(ta1)@}\) is appropriate for the denominator. &lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Finally, to find \(n\) we look at the final term and compare it to the typical term we have found \(\displaystyle {@ta1@}\). We can see that by letting \(p={@bound1@}\) we obtain \(\displaystyle {@ser1(bound1)@}\), so \(n={@bound1@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Hence, the summation form of this series is \[\displaystyle \sum_{p~=~1}^{{@bound1@}} {@ta1@}\]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;

    &lt;li&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Similarly, looking at the numerators for the first three terms we see that it is either \({@num(ser2(1))@}\) or \({@num(ser2(2))@}\) for odd and even values of \(p\), respectively, which can be expressed as \({@num(ta2)@}\). And looking at the
            denominators we find that they can be expressed as \({@denom(ta2)@}\).&lt;/p&gt;

        &lt;p&gt;By letting \(p={@bound2@}\), in our newly found typical term \(\displaystyle {@ta2@}\) we obtain the final term \(\displaystyle {@ser2(bound2)@}\). So \(n={@bound2@}\).&lt;/p&gt;

        &lt;p&gt;Hence, the summation form of this series is \[\displaystyle \sum_{p~=~1}^{{@bound2@}} {@ta2@}\]&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</generalfeedback>
